      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "d7ca9fa0228a6a0f",
      "text": "A solution is an answer to a problem. (Merriam-Webster Dictionary 2020) [https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/solution page]"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "1d6fd2265533e7a0",
      "text": "> 1 a: an action or process of solving a problem\nb: an answer to a problem : [[Explanation]]\nspecifically : a set of values of the variables that satisfies an equation\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "dc8b8f77dff53d76",
      "text": "The concept of [[Solution]] implies another concept—the concept of [[Problem]] to which a solution responds. While problems are discrepancies between a desired (future) state and an undesirable (present) state, solutions are sought and established to address corresponding problems."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "de7a3d0ea508b9c8",
      "text": "Both problem and solution are abstract concepts that are mutually dependent. While a problem is represented by carefully formulated conditions such as requirements or constraints, a problem calls for a solution. A solution responds to an associated problem by providing capabilities that address the problem’s conditions. A solution, in essence, is anything addressing a problem. Architecture assets are a common means of creating solutions in modern enterprise contexts (Fig. 6.51)."
    },
    {
      "type": "image",
      "id": "b00d312080d6d925",
      "text": "Fig. 6.51 Problem-solution dichotomy",
      "size": "wide",
      "width": 418,
      "height": 209,
      "url": "/assets/plugins/image/cfbb3eb6a60a91101223182c845c35e7.jpg"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "31cb03e4bd23ef45",
      "text": "Architecture assets realize capabilities (solution), and capabilities address conditions (problem). An asset (as a whole or in parts) realizes one or more capabilities. Conversely, a single capability can be realized jointly by multiple assets. Similarly, a capability addresses (in whole or in part) one or more conditions, which means that a single condition can also be addressed jointly by multiple capabilities (Fig. 6.52)."
    },
